        double result = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return result % 1 == 0 && n > 0;
    }
}
```

### Explanation

This solution uses the mathematical property that a number `n` is a power of three if and only if `log(n) / log(3)` is an integer. In Java, we can use the! `Math.log` function to compute the natural logarithm of a number. We then divide the result by `Math.log(3)` to get the base-3 logarithm of `n`. If `n` is a power of three, this result will be an integer (i.e., `result % 1 == 0`). We also check that `n` is positive.

Note that this solution assumes that the input number `n` is within the range of the `int` data type. If `n` is outside this range, the `Math.log` function may return `NaN` (Not a Number) or throw an exception.

